Of the Galgulus the size is almost that of the Turtur: it is yellowish in colour, and hacks timber very much, and for the most part feeds on trees: it utters a loud cry. This bird is mainly an inhabitant of the Peloponnese.

All that Aristotle has so far attributed to the Colius or Galgulus is in agreement with the Huhol of the English and the Grunspecht of the Germans (if one may except its being chiefly an inhabitant of the Peloponnese). For it is nearly equal to the Turtle—Dove in size3 it hacks the timber, hammers rotten wood, and utters a loud cry. But Ι give no decision here, Ι only ask. The Galgulus of Pliny is said to be called the Icteros in Greek, and if we trust to Theodorus [Gaza] is also the κελεός of Aristotle.
